title.narrative: HEALTH SERVICES TO NEW-BORNS, UNDER-FIVE CHILDREN, PREGNANT MOTHERS & ADOLESCENTS

description.narrative: Output 1.1: By 2023, Government and partners have improved capacity to provide quality health services for new-borns, under-five children, pregnant mothers, including health services that are adolescent-friendly, which contributes to Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Immunization (Covid), Maternal And Newborn Health, Maternal And Newborn Health (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 101: By 2023, newborns, children, adolescents and women, especially the most vulnerable, increasingly benefit from quality, inclusive and gender-responsive health, nutrition and improved WASH

description.narrative: Despite the COVID-19 pandemic emergency, essential health services including immunization for newborn, children and women were continued. Improved skill of health workers and no stock out of vaccines has facilitated in providing quality health care services and maintaining high coverage of immunization. Timely procurement of critical medical supplies has supported in accessing testing facility for COVID-19 and use of personal protection equipment by health workers. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:28/08/2020
